properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow and strong winds are expected. Total snowfall: 5 to 10 cm possible. Maximum wind gusts: 80 to 100 km/h in the Rigolet area and 100 to 120 km/h from Cartwright to Black Tickle. Time span: Saturday evening until early Sunday morning. Remarks: After a brief period of snow and rain tonight, conditions will improve for most of Saturday. However, snow is expected to develop again on Saturday evening with strong northwesterly winds. Snow and blowing snow may significantly reduce visibility for several hours on Saturday night. Wind warnings are anticipated; blowing snow advisories may also be required. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
Expires: 2019-11-16T06:49:35-00:00
Originated from CAP Alert: Environment Canada, 2019-11-15T14:50:35-00:00, urn:oid:2.49.0.1.124.1412782746.2019
Area: Cartwright to Black Tickle, Rigolet and vicinity

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow, blowing snow and strong northwesterly winds are expected. Total snowfall: 20 to 30 cm. Maximum wind gusts: 120 km/h. Locations: Hopedale to Makkovik. Time span: overnight tonight until early Sunday. Remarks: Snow will begin this evening before strong northwesterly winds develop overnight to cause poor visibility in blowing snow. Stormy conditions will persist through Saturday and then improve overnight Saturday night into early Sunday. ### Visibility will be suddenly reduced to near zero at times in heavy snow and blowing snow. Winter storm warnings are issued when multiple types of severe winter weather are expected to occur together. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant high-elevation snowfall is expected. Total snowfall: near 5 cm, except 15 to 25 cm over higher terrain. Time span: this evening until Saturday night. Locations: Bonne Bay to Hawke's Bay. Remarks: Rain will begin this evening over coastal areas while snow will develop over the Long Range Mountains. Precipitation will transition to flurries over all areas by Saturday morning. Flurries will then continue through Saturday with possible snow squalls, before gradually easing Saturday night. Anyone using the Viking Trail through Gros Morne National Park or high-elevation backcountry trails should be prepared for winter travel conditions. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Snow Squall Watch In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Brief, intense snowfall is expected to develop. Under the snow squall, visibilities will be significantly reduced due to the heavy snow. A brief snow squall giving a quick 2 cm of snow is possible as a sharp arctic cold front blasts southeast across the region this afternoon. Motorists should be prepared for sudden very low to nil visibility in a burst of heavy snow as the snow squall moves through. ### Travel may be hazardous due to sudden changes in the weather. Snow squall watches are issued when conditions are favourable for the formation of bands of snow that could produce intense accumulating snow or near zero visibilities. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: A short period of rain is expected, followed by wintry conditions. Total rainfall: 10 to 20 mm. Total snowfall: near 5 cm, except 10 cm or more over higher terrain. Locations: Bay St. George to the Bay of Islands. Time span: early this evening until Saturday evening. Remarks: Rain will begin this evening. In light of the flooding early this week, some areas may still be sensitive to any rainfall that occurs. Interests in these locations should monitor local runoff for any potential vulnerabilities. The rain will transition to flurries later tonight or early Saturday, with possible snow squalls during the day on Saturday. The flurries will taper off Saturday night. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
